<se_def>*: Grrrr...
<se_def>*: (Hiss!)
<se_def>*: Ssss!
<se_def>*: GRRRRRRRRR!
<se_def>*: Grr!
<se_def>*: Howzit? Welcome to Chateau Felix! Residence of the great sabrecat father, Master Felix!
<se_def>*: My name's Tom. I'm Master Felix's helper. Are you here to see him?
<se_def>Tom: Ahem!? Then what are you doing here!? You better scat now now!
<se_def>Tom: Ahem! Excuse me! Bit of catarrh.
<se_def>Tom: But Master Felix is a busy man! He hasn't got time to meet any old thing the cat dragged in!
<se_def>Tom: I'll have to ask you some questions. If you can prove you're a top cat, I'll let you in just now.
<se_def>Tom: Question number one!
<se_def>Tom: It's late and it's raining cats and dogs. You're hurrying home, when you hear a little kitten meowing. It's right soaking wet.
<se_def>Tom: But everyone in your house really hates cats. So, what do you do with the kitten?

<se_def>Pretend not to have seen it.
Move it to a sheltered place out of the rain.
Take it home and ask your family to let it stay.
<se_def>Tom: AHEM!
<se_def>Tom: Question number two!
<se_def>Tom: You're the King's servant. You go out hunting with the King, but don't manage to find any prey.
<se_def>Tom: Then you find a tiger in a trap in the woods! The King is some way off and hasn't noticed the tiger yet.
<se_def>Tom: So, what do you do?

<se_def>Let the tiger live but show it to the King.
Kill the tiger and then show it to the King.
Free the tiger from the trap and let it go.
<se_def>Tom: AHEM!
<se_def>Tom: And question number three!
<se_def>Tom: You are an explorer. Along your travels you're attacked by a great sabrecat.
<se_def>Tom: You manage to overpower the cat, but then it looks at you as if it wants to become your friend and travel with you.
<se_def>Tom: So, what do you do?

<se_def>Let the great sabrecat join you on your travels.
Leave without it.
Deliver the finishing blow.
<se_def>Tom: AHEM!
<se_def>Tom: And now to let the cat out of the bag! Let's see how you did!
<se_def>Tom: I'm sorry, but you're not the kind of person Master Felix has the time to meet.
<se_def>Tom: I can't let you in to see him meow. Sorry.
<se_def>Tom: If you really want to see him, have another go at my test.
<se_def>Tom: Purrrfect! You've proved that you're the cat's whiskers, a real hip-cat!
<se_def>Tom: Ahem! You have permission to see Master Felix. You can go in.
<se_def>Tom: AHEM!
<se_def>Tom: Howzit!? You want to try my test again?
<se_def>Tom: No!? Suffering cats! If you've got nothing to do here, you better scat now now!
<se_def>Tom: Ahem! Okay! Here we go!
<se_def>Tom: I don't know where he got the name from, but people call Master Felix the great sabrecat father.
<se_def>Tom: Nobody knows why.
<se_def>*: Rrr... rrrRRRAAAAARRRR!
<se_def>*: Grrrr...
<se_low>*: ...Hm?
<se_low>*: I say, someone other than Tom for once! The old boy doesn't often let people in, you know!
<se_low>*: You've caught me at a rather busy time, I'm afraid. I'll be with you in a jiffy.

<se_low>*: There!
   I think I'll take a breather for a while.
   Sorry to keep you waiting.

<se_low>*: So, you're an explorer, eh!?
   I'm Felix.
<se_low>Felix: ...Well, well! Tom's really got an eye for people! Only lets decent chaps through, you know!
<se_low>Felix: Yes... You might just be able to assist me. There's a little undertaking I need some help with. Allow me to explain...
<se_low>Felix: It's an old chum of mine, you see. Gone and got himself lost, would you believe.
<se_low>Felix: Normally I'd go and help the old bean out myself of course, but as you can see, I've got a lot on my plate just at the mo.
<se_low>Felix: That's where you come in. I'd like you to go and give the old bean a bit of assistance. If you don't mind, that is...
<se_low>Felix: Well? What do you say? Will you help?
<se_low>Felix: I see... Well, that's a bally shame. I suppose I'll just have to go and do it myself.
<se_low>Felix: Can't force you, what. Take care, then! Chin up, and all that!
<se_low>Felix: Capital! Right, I'll tell you what I need you to do then.
<se_low>Felix: Around these parts, there are four great sabrecat statues. You might have seen one of them on your way over here.
<se_low>Felix: They all point to the same place. There's a strange tree there that's only visible at dawn.<page>Felix: And that's precisely where the old chap is, you see.
<se_low>Felix: All I need you to do is go there and give him this.
<se_low>Felix: He's a clever old bean. Just give him that and he'll know what to do.
<se_low>Felix: Once you've given it to him, come back and pay me a visit. I'll have a little token of appreciation for you.
<se_low>Felix: If you leave here and head up the hill you'll get a view of a couple of the sabrecat statues.<page>Felix: It's worth taking a look before you go off exploring!
<se_low>Felix: Eh? Oh, I say! You again! Have you had a change of heart!? You'd like to help now, would you?
<se_low>Felix: No? Then please be kind enough not to disturb me! I've got things to do, hm!
<se_low>Felix: Oh, I say! You're still here! You haven't forgotten what I asked, have you? I'd better explain it again, eh?
<se_low>Felix: Go and find yourself a decent vantage point, somewhere high up, and you should be able to see the great sabrecat statues.
<se_low>Felix: In the middle of the four statues is a strange tree that's only visible at dawn. And that's where you'll find my old friend.
<se_low>Felix: Just give the old chap the sand of serenity and Bob's your uncle!
<se_low>Felix: It's rather tedious that you can only see the tree at dawn, but I'm afraid there's no way around it, <IF_MALE>old chap<ELSE_NOT_MALE>my girl<ENDIF_MALE>.
<se_def>*: Purr purr.
<se_def>Tom: Ahem? Wasn't Master Felix inside!?
<se_def>Tom: ...Whaaat!? Master Felix asked you a favour!?
<se_def>Tom: He must think you're the cat's pyjamas if he gave you the go-ahead to ride one of his great sabrecats!
<se_def>Tom: Howzit? So you're back. Master Felix is waiting for you inside, bru.
<se_low>Felix: What ho! Finally made it back, I see. And you managed to give my old chum a leg up.
<se_low>Felix: That strange tree where you met him has been known since ancient times as the Tree of Styx.
<se_low>Felix: It's all too bally easy to lose your way around it, not realising that your innings is over.
<se_low>Felix: But now the old bean's realised what's happened to him and he's safely on his way to the afterlife.
<se_low>Felix: You know, he...Baumren...was the first sabrecat ever to open up his heart to me. Absolutely terrific chap!
<se_low>Felix: It's thanks to him that I've got where I am today.
<se_low>Felix: And that's precisely why I couldn't leave the job unattended to go and help the old boy myself.
<se_low>Felix: ...Hm? What am I doing? Of course! I haven't explained yet, eh!?
<se_low>Felix: I'm the chairman of the Great Sabrecat Trust! I know! Why don't I make you a member? It's the least I can do after all your help!
<se_low>Felix: You have this! It shows you're one of us.
<se_low>Felix: With that, you'll be able to call on another member anywhere in the world. Jolly useful, what?
<se_low>Felix: Once you get outside, just show that ribbon to Tom. He'll know what to do.
<se_low>Felix: Ah! I'm sure you've got better things to do than hang around here, eh!
<se_low>Felix: I've dedicated my whole life to sabrecats! They're very dear to me, very dear indeed.
<se_low>Felix: Now that you're a member of the Trust, I trust you'll feel the same way, what!
<se_def>Tom: AHEM! So you've joined the Great Sabrecat Trust?
<se_def>Tom: You're fixed up now with that bell. You can call any sabrecat in the world to come and help you. No need to borrow them from here any more.
<se_def>Tom: Good luck then, bru. Come back and visit Master Felix sometimes.
